Perpetuity, otherwise known as *consols* refers to a constant annuity without maturity. Hence, if the period is forever, the cash flow will be constant and have infinite periods. For that reason, in this calculation, we will use the present value of a perpetuity formula presented below:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of Perpetuity} &=\dfrac{\text{Cash amount}}{\text{Rate}}

\end{aligned}$$

Using the present value perpetuity formula, let's determine the present value of the investment if the term is forever.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of Perpetuity} &= \dfrac{\text{\$4,350}}{.06}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$72,500}
\end{aligned}$$

**Hence, the value of the investment if perpetuity is $72,500.**
